  <!-- ══ ARTICLE BODY ══ -->
  <article class="art-sec art-sec--white">
    <div class="art-wrap art-layout">

      <!-- MAIN CONTENT -->
      <div class="art-content">

        <!-- § 1 -->
        <section id="what-hospital-doors-need" class="art-section">
          <h2>What Hospital Doors Must Deliver</h2>
          <p class="art-lead-p">
            A hospital door is opened and closed hundreds of times a day, struck by trolleys and wheelchairs, exposed to aggressive cleaning chemicals, and expected to prevent the spread of fire, infection, and — in specialist departments — ionising radiation. No other door in any building type is asked to do more.
          </p>
          <p>
            Specifying correctly requires understanding the distinct performance layers a healthcare door must satisfy simultaneously. Miss one layer and the door either fails inspection, creates an infection risk, or becomes a liability in the event of fire.
          </p>

          <div class="art-req-grid">
            <div class="art-req-card">
              <div class="art-req-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">🦠</div>
              <strong>Infection Control</strong>
              <p>Antibacterial surface films, smooth flush profiles with no crevices, and chemical-resistant finishes that withstand repeated disinfection with hospital-grade cleaning agents.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="art-req-card">
              <div class="art-req-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">🔥</div>
              <strong>Fire Containment</strong>
              <p>FD30 (30-minute) and FD60 (60-minute) rated door sets in corridors, stairwells, and plant rooms — tested to EN 1634-1 and supplied with certified intumescent seals and closers.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="art-req-card">
              <div class="art-req-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">☢️</div>
              <strong>Radiation Shielding</strong>
              <p>Lead-lined door leaves and frames for radiology suites, CT rooms, nuclear medicine, and radiotherapy — specified in millimetres of lead equivalency (mmPb).</p>
            </div>
            <div class="art-req-card">
              <div class="art-req-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">♿</div>
              <strong>Accessibility</strong>
              <p>Wider clear openings (min. 900 mm for wheelchair access), low-energy or power-assisted openers, and vision panels at two heights per accessibility standards.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="art-req-card">
              <div class="art-req-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">💪</div>
              <strong>Impact Resistance</strong>
              <p>Full-height stainless steel kick-plates, PVC bump guards, and reinforced door edges to withstand the daily impact of beds, trolleys, and medical equipment.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="art-req-card">
              <div class="art-req-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">🔇</div>
              <strong>Acoustic Performance</strong>
              <p>Acoustic seals on patient room and consultation room doors to provide speech privacy — typically Rw 32–42 dB depending on application.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- § 2 -->
        <section id="door-types" class="art-section">
          <h2>Hospital Door Types by Department</h2>
          <p>
            Different areas of a hospital have fundamentally different requirements. A one-size-fits-all approach leads to over-specified (and expensive) doors in low-risk areas, and dangerously under-specified doors where it matters most.
          </p>

          <div class="art-dept-list">
            <div class="art-dept">
              <div class="art-dept__head">
                <span class="art-dept__num">01</span>
                <h3>Patient Rooms & Ward Corridors</h3>
              </div>
              <p>Standard flush MDF-PVC doors with antibacterial film, vision panel, stainless kick-plate, and FD30 rating where required by layout. Colour-coded finishes assist wayfinding. Typically 900–1000 mm clear opening width.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="art-dept">
              <div class="art-dept__head">
                <span class="art-dept__num">02</span>
                <h3>Operating Theatres</h3>
              </div>
              <p>Hermetically sealed swing or sliding doors with full perimeter seals, stainless steel cladding, and access control integration. Positive pressure differential management is critical — door seals must be airtight. Special hygienic frames with no exposed fixings.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="art-dept">
              <div class="art-dept__head">
                <span class="art-dept__num">03</span>
                <h3>Intensive Care Units (ICU)</h3>
              </div>
              <p>Wide double-leaf sets (min. 1200 mm clear) for bed passage, full-length vision panels for patient observation, and acoustic seals. ICU doors often combine FD60 fire rating with acoustic performance and antibacterial finishes.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="art-dept">
              <div class="art-dept__head">
                <span class="art-dept__num">04</span>
                <h3>Radiology & Imaging</h3>
              </div>
              <p>Lead-lined door sets to shield adjacent areas from ionising radiation. CT, MRI, fluoroscopy, and plain X-ray rooms each have different shielding requirements specified by the radiation physicist. Doors are typically single-leaf 1000 mm wide, with matching lead-lined frames and threshold.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="art-dept">
              <div class="art-dept__head">
                <span class="art-dept__num">05</span>
                <h3>Pharmacy & Clean Rooms</h3>
              </div>
              <p>Smooth, cleanable surfaces with no recessed handles or projections that could harbour contamination. Positive pressure vestibule doors, interlocked air-lock systems, and ESD (electrostatic discharge) resistant finishes where required.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="art-dept">
              <div class="art-dept__head">
                <span class="art-dept__num">06</span>
                <h3>Emergency & Trauma</h3>
              </div>
              <p>Heavy-duty impact-resistant doors designed for constant high-traffic use. Power-assisted operation for hands-free entry in emergency situations. Robust stainless steel hardware rated for 1,000,000+ operation cycles.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- § 3 -->
        <section id="lead-lined" class="art-section">
          <h2>Lead-Lined Doors: X-Ray & Radiation Shielding</h2>
          <p>
            Radiology departments represent the most technically demanding door specification in any hospital project. The door is not merely a physical barrier — it is a radiation shield, and its performance must be verified by a qualified medical physics engineer.
          </p>

          <div class="art-highlight">
            <div class="art-highlight__icon" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/><line x1="12" y1="8" x2="12" y2="12"/><line x1="12" y1="16" x2="12.01" y2="16"/></svg>
            </div>
            <p>Lead equivalency for hospital doors is expressed in millimetres of lead (mmPb). A 1.0 mmPb door is suitable for most plain X-ray rooms; CT scanner rooms typically require 2.0–3.0 mmPb. The radiation physicist's report governs the specification — never the architect's assumption.</p>
          </div>

          <h3>Construction of a Lead-Lined Door</h3>
          <p>
            CihanPan Door's lead-lined sets are built around an MDF core with continuous lead sheet bonded between the inner and outer door skins. The lead sheet runs edge-to-edge and top-to-bottom with no gaps — overlapping at joints to prevent radiation streaming. The door face is finished in smooth PVC or laminate for easy cleaning.
          </p>
          <ul class="art-list">
            <li><strong>Lead equivalency range:</strong> 0.5 mmPb to 4.0 mmPb supplied as standard; higher specifications on request.</li>
            <li><strong>Frame lining:</strong> Matching lead-lined frames and architraves ensure continuous shielding around the full door opening.</li>
            <li><strong>Vision panel:</strong> Lead glass or barium glass inserts maintain shielding integrity while allowing observation.</li>
            <li><strong>Certification:</strong> Each door set is supplied with a radiation physics certificate confirming measured attenuation.</li>
            <li><strong>Weight:</strong> A 1.0 mmPb single-leaf door weighs approximately 60–80 kg — heavy-duty hinges and closers are included as standard.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- § 4 -->
        <section id="fire-rated" class="art-section">
          <h2>Fire-Rated Hospital Doors: FD30 & FD60</h2>
          <p>
            Fire compartmentation is mandatory in all hospital buildings. The door is the weakest point in any fire-rated wall — and the one most frequently left open, propped, or damaged. Turkish manufacturers supply complete certified door sets (leaf, frame, seals, hardware) that have been tested as a system, not as individual components.
          </p>

          <div class="art-fire-grid">
            <div class="art-fire-card art-fire-card--fd30">
              <div class="art-fire-card__badge">FD30</div>
              <h3>30-Minute Fire Door</h3>
              <p>Suitable for most ward corridors, patient room doors in compartmented layouts, and general circulation areas. Tested to EN 1634-1. Intumescent strip and smoke seal included.</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Ward corridors</li>
                <li>Patient bedrooms</li>
                <li>General offices</li>
                <li>Storage rooms</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="art-fire-card art-fire-card--fd60">
              <div class="art-fire-card__badge">FD60</div>
              <h3>60-Minute Fire Door</h3>
              <p>Required at compartment boundaries, stairwell enclosures, plant rooms, and high-risk areas. Heavier construction with additional intumescent layers. Certified self-closing devices mandatory.</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Stairwell enclosures</li>
                <li>Plant & electrical rooms</li>
                <li>Compartment walls</li>
                <li>ICU & theatre lobbies</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>
            All fire-rated door sets are supplied with the EN 1634-1 test certificate, CE Declaration of Performance, and a door schedule showing hardware specifications. Third-party installation inspection is recommended and documentation is provided to support the building's fire safety file.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- § 5 -->
        <section id="cihanpan" class="art-section">
          <h2>CihanPan Door: Healthcare Division</h2>
          <p>
            CihanPan Door operates a dedicated healthcare division within its Kayseri manufacturing facility. The division was established in response to growing demand from hospital developers and international healthcare contractors who needed a single supplier capable of covering the full door schedule — from standard ward doors to specialist lead-lined radiology sets.
          </p>

          <div class="art-brand-block">
            <div class="art-brand-block__accent" aria-hidden="true"></div>
            <blockquote class="art-brand-block__quote">
              "Every hospital door we supply has a person's life on the other side of it. That is not a responsibility we take lightly."
            </blockquote>
            <cite class="art-brand-block__cite">— CihanPan Door Healthcare Division, Kayseri</cite>
            <a href="https://www.cihanpandoor.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="art-brand-block__link">
              www.cihanpandoor.com
              <svg width="13" height="13" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M18 13v6a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H5a2 2 0 0 1-2-2V8a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h6"/><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"/><line x1="10" y1="14" x2="21" y2="3"/></svg>
            </a>
          </div>

          <h3>Healthcare Capabilities at a Glance</h3>
          <ul class="art-list art-list--check">
            <li><strong>Full door schedule supply</strong> — standard ward, fire-rated, acoustic, lead-lined, and hermetic doors from one manufacturer, simplifying procurement and ensuring finish consistency.</li>
            <li><strong>In-house lead lining</strong> — lead sheet bonding is performed in-factory, not outsourced, ensuring quality control and competitive lead times.</li>
            <li><strong>BIM object library</strong> — Revit families available for all standard healthcare door types, supporting the design team from RIBA Stage 2 onward.</li>
            <li><strong>Project scheduling</strong> — phased delivery aligned to construction programme; doors for each ward block delivered in installation sequence.</li>
            <li><strong>Post-installation support</strong> — adjustment service and replacement hardware available for the life of the building.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- § 6 Buying Guide -->
        <section id="buying-guide" class="art-section">
          <h2>Procurement Guide: Specifying Hospital Doors from Turkey</h2>

          <div class="art-steps">
            <div class="art-step">
              <div class="art-step__num">1</div>
              <div class="art-step__body">
                <strong>Prepare a door schedule</strong>
                <p>List every door opening: room reference, clear width, clear height, fire rating, acoustic requirement, vision panel, hardware, and any specialist requirements (lead lining, hermetic sealing). A complete schedule dramatically reduces quotation turnaround time.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="art-step">
              <div class="art-step__num">2</div>
              <div class="art-step__body">
                <strong>Obtain the radiation physics report early</strong>
                <p>For any radiology or nuclear medicine areas, the medical physics engineer's shielding report must be issued before door specification is finalised. Lead equivalency cannot be assumed — it must be calculated for each room based on equipment type and workload.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="art-step">
              <div class="art-step__num">3</div>
              <div class="art-step__body">
                <strong>Request full system certification</strong>
                <p>Ask for EN 1634-1 fire test certificates, CE Declarations of Performance, radiation attenuation certificates (for lead-lined doors), and ISO 9001 factory audit reports. Reputable Turkish manufacturers hold all of these as standard.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="art-step">
              <div class="art-step__num">4</div>
              <div class="art-step__body">
                <strong>Align delivery with programme</strong>
                <p>Hospital projects are phased. Agree a delivery schedule by zone or ward rather than a single bulk delivery — this reduces on-site storage requirements and the risk of damage to doors before installation.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="art-step">
              <div class="art-step__num">5</div>
              <div class="art-step__body">
                <strong>Plan for installation inspection</strong>
                <p>Fire-rated and lead-lined doors must be installed correctly to perform as tested. Budget for a third-party installation inspection and ensure the contractor is familiar with the specific system being installed.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="art-cta-inline">
            <p>Ready to discuss your hospital door schedule?</p>
            <a href="https://www.cihanpandoor.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="art-btn art-btn--gold">
              Contact CihanPan Door
              <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M18 13v6a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H5a2 2 0 0 1-2-2V8a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h6"/><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"/><line x1="10" y1="14" x2="21" y2="3"/></svg>
            </a>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- § FAQ -->
        <section id="faq" class="art-section">
          <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

          <div class="art-faq">
            <details class="art-faq__item">
              <summary class="art-faq__q">What makes a door suitable for hospital use?</summary>
              <div class="art-faq__a">
                <p>Hospital doors must meet stringent hygiene, durability, and safety standards. Key requirements include antibacterial surface coatings, easy-clean smooth finishes, impact-resistant kick-plates, appropriate fire ratings (typically FD30 or FD60), and in specialist areas such as radiology, lead lining for radiation shielding.</p>
              </div>
            </details>
            <details class="art-faq__item">
              <summary class="art-faq__q">Do Turkish hospital doors meet international standards?</summary>
              <div class="art-faq__a">
                <p>Yes. Leading Turkish manufacturers including CihanPan Door produce hospital doors to EN 1634-1 fire test standards, ISO 9001 quality management systems, and CE marking requirements. Many products are also tested to BS 8300 accessibility guidelines for healthcare environments.</p>
              </div>
            </details>
            <details class="art-faq__item">
              <summary class="art-faq__q">Can CihanPan Door supply lead-lined X-ray room doors?</summary>
              <div class="art-faq__a">
                <p>Yes. CihanPan Door manufactures lead-lined door sets for radiology departments, CT scan rooms, and nuclear medicine areas. Lead equivalency is specified per project — typically 1.0 mm to 3.0 mm Pb — and verified with radiation physics certificates.</p>
              </div>
            </details>
            <details class="art-faq__item">
              <summary class="art-faq__q">What is the lead time for hospital door projects?</summary>
              <div class="art-faq__a">
                <p>Standard ward doors typically have a 3–5 week lead time from order confirmation. Specialist doors (lead-lined, hermetic, acoustic) require 5–8 weeks. For large hospital projects, a phased production schedule is agreed at the time of order to align with the construction programme.</p>
              </div>
            </details>
            <details class="art-faq__item">
              <summary class="art-faq__q">What is the minimum order quantity for hospital door projects?</summary>
              <div class="art-faq__a">
                <p>CihanPan Door works with healthcare projects of all sizes, from single-ward refurbishments to full hospital builds. For export orders, a minimum of one 20-foot container (approximately 100–150 door sets) is typical, though project-specific arrangements are possible.</p>
              </div>
            </details>
          </div>
        </section>

      </div><!-- /art-content -->

      <!-- SIDEBAR -->
      <aside class="art-sidebar" aria-label="Article sidebar">
        <div class="art-sidebar__card art-sidebar__card--cta">
          <p class="art-sidebar__eyebrow">Healthcare Projects</p>
